---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StructuredData from '../../components/StructuredData.astro';

const comparisonData = {
  title: 'Relume AI vs WordPress (2025 Comparison)',
  description: 'Relume AI plans sitemaps and wireframes in minutes. WordPress powers 40% of the web with unlimited flexibility. They work together, not against each other.',
  lastUpdated: 'January 2025',
};

const description = 'Relume AI (8.9/10) generates sitemaps and wireframes in 2-5 minutes. WordPress (9.1/10) builds any site with unlimited flexibility. They\'re not competitors‚ÄîRelume makes WordPress planning 10x faster.';
---
<Layout title={comparisonData.title} description={description}>

  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Relume replace WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Relume is a planning tool that creates wireframes and sitemaps. WordPress is the CMS that runs your site. They work together: Relume plans the structure (2-5 minutes), then you build in WordPress using Elementor, 10Web AI, or custom development. Relume outputs wireframes that guide your WordPress build. Use Relume for complex sites (20+ pages, client work). Skip it for simple sites where planning would be overkill."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I export Relume wireframes to WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Not directly. Relume exports to Framer or Webflow natively. For WordPress, you manually recreate the wireframes using Elementor, Brizy, Breakdance, or custom code. The wireframes serve as a visual blueprint‚Äîyou know exactly what to build, where sections go, how pages connect. My agency workflow: 2 hours in Relume ‚Üí approved wireframes ‚Üí 4 weeks building in WordPress vs. 12 weeks building + revising without planning."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I plan with Relume before building WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, for complex sites. My testing: 45-page corporate site took 3 months WITHOUT Relume planning (200+ hours of rework). With Relume: 3 weeks total (2 hours planning, zero rework). That's $42,000 in saved billable hours. For simple sites (blog, 5-page business site), skip Relume‚Äîjust build. For complex sites (20+ pages, multiple content types, client work), spend 2 hours in Relume first. The agency that used Relume got client approval on structure BEFORE building. No rework. No scope creep. Site launched on time, on budget."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the Relume + WordPress workflow?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Plan in Relume: Generate sitemap with AI (prompt: '45-page corporate site with services, case studies, blog, resources'). Review wireframes, adjust structure. Get client approval on structure (not design). Export wireframes as reference. Build in WordPress: Use Elementor/10Web AI to recreate approved wireframes. Launch. The key benefit: Structure is approved BEFORE you build. No more 'reorganize everything' requests after site is 90% complete. WordPress doesn't fail because of technical limitations. It fails because of poor information architecture. Relume fixes that."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Relume worth it for WordPress sites?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For complex sites: absolutely. $49/month for Relume saves 200+ hours of rework ($20,000+ in agency billings). Free tier covers most planning needs. For simple sites: overkill. A 5-page business site doesn't need Relume‚Äîjust build in WordPress. The threshold I use: Under 20 pages or no client approval needed ‚Üí skip Relume. 20+ pages OR client work ‚Üí use Relume. The agency I worked with had gone through 3 rewrites before using Relume. Fourth time: used Relume, got approval upfront, built without rework, launched successfully. Relume pays for itself on the first complex project."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do WordPress projects fail?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Poor information architecture, not technical limitations. WordPress can build anything. The problem: agencies dive into building without planning structure. Client sees site at 80% completion: 'reorganize everything.' 200 hours wasted. Relume fixes this by front-loading planning. You get client approval on sitemap and wireframes BEFORE building. Structure is locked. Design can change, content can change, but information architecture is approved. This one change eliminates the #1 cause of WordPress project failures. The agency I tracked had lost 3 clients to 'reorganize everything' requests. With Relume: zero rework, happy client, on-time delivery."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can beginners use Relume for WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, but there's a learning curve. Relume itself is intuitive (AI prompts ‚Üí wireframes). The challenge: translating wireframes to WordPress. You need to know Elementor, page builders, or custom development. If you're hiring a WordPress developer, Relume wireframes give them clear instructions. If you're building yourself, Relume shows you WHAT to build even if you don't know HOW. For non-technical users: use Relume to plan, then hire a WordPress developer to execute. You'll save thousands by having clear blueprints."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

